        "assistant": "# Prismatic Affinity\n\nA **prismatic affinity** is a type of geometric transformation in affine geometry. Specifically, it's an affine transformation of space that:\n\n- **Fixes every point** of a given plane (called the **base plane** or **plane of affinity**)\n- **Maps every line in a fixed direction** (the **direction of affinity**) to itself\n- The direction of affinity is **parallel** to the base plane (this is what makes it \"prismatic\")\n\n## Key Characteristics\n\n1. **Invariant plane**: Every point on the base plane stays exactly where it is.\n2. **Invariant direction**: Lines parallel to the direction of affinity slide along themselves.\n3. **Parallelism condition**: Because the direction of affinity is parallel to (not crossing) the base plane, points off the plane get translated parallel to the plane.\n\n## How It Differs from a Homological Affinity\n\n- In an **oblique (homological) affinity**, the direction of affinity intersects the base plane.\n- In a **prismatic affinity**, the direction is parallel to the base plane — so points away from the plane shift by an amount proportional to their distance from the plane, but always in the same parallel direction.\n\n## Geometric Effect\n\nIf you imagine a solid above the base plane, a prismatic affinity shears it: each \"layer\" parallel to the base plane slides by an amount that depends linearly on its height. This is essentially a **shear transformation** in 3D, where the shearing happens along a direction parallel to the invariant plane.\n\n## Applications\n\nPrismatic affinities are studied in:\n- **Descriptive geometry** (especially in European traditions, such as Spanish and Italian geometry textbooks)\n- **Projective and affine geometry**\n- **Engineering drawing** for analyzing oblique projections and shears\n\nWould you like a concrete example with coordinates, or a comparison with other affinities?",
