        "user": "How does \"prismatic affinity\" differ from polysemy?",
        "assistant": "Same standing caveat: I'm working from your stipulated definition, treating \"prismatic affinity\" as a proposed concept rather than an established term.\n\n## Polysemy\n\n- A property of **signs, words, or symbols** that carry multiple related meanings.\n- The meanings are typically **listed or enumerable** — a dictionary can catalogue them (e.g., \"bank\" as financial institution, river edge, act of tilting an aircraft).\n- Which meaning is active is usually settled by **linguistic or pragmatic context**.\n- The multiple meanings coexist as a stable feature of the sign; they don't shift dynamically with how the interpreter attends.\n- Polysemy is primarily a **semantic** phenomenon, located in language.\n\n## Prismatic affinity (per your stipulation)\n\n- A property of a **perceived object**, not a sign or word.\n- The shifting identities are **not enumerable in advance** — they're generated by the angle of attention brought to bear, in principle open-ended.\n- What selects the active identity is **the framing of attention**, not linguistic context.\n- It's a **phenomenological or perceptual** phenomenon, not a semantic one.\n\n## The core contrasts\n\n1. **Locus**: polysemy lives in *signs*; prismatic affinity lives in *the object-attention relation*.\n2. **Enumerability**: polysemous meanings are catalogable; prismatically affine identities are generated by framing and may not be exhaustively listable.\n3. **Selection mechanism**: polysemy resolves through linguistic/pragmatic context; prismatic affinity resolves through attentional framing.\n4. **Relation between readings**: polysemous senses are typically *related* (etymologically, metaphorically) but distinct; prismatically affine identities are described as **non-overlapping yet internally consistent** — a stronger claim of mutual completeness.\n\n## A nearby case worth distinguishing\n\nPolysemy has a cousin, **homonymy**, where meanings are unrelated (the two \"banks\" of \"bank\"). Prismatic affinity isn't quite either: the identities aren't unrelated (they're identities of *the same object*) but they also aren't merely related senses of one thing — they're claimed to be coherent wholes.\n\n## A pressure point\n\nThe concept needs to do work that polysemy can't already do under a generous reading. One could argue: \"polysemy of the perceived object\" — i.e., extending polysemy from signs to perceptual objects — already captures much of what you're after. To earn its keep, prismatic affinity needs the **non-overlapping yet internally complete** clause to carry real weight: polysemous senses *can* overlap and be partial, while prismatically affine identities supposedly cannot. Whether perceptual experience actually presents identities that are simultaneously non-overlapping *and* internally complete — rather than partial, blended, or competing — is an empirical-phenomenological question your definition stipulates an answer to rather than argues for.\n\nThat's the seam I'd probe if you're refining the concept.",
