        "assistant": "# Prismatic Affinity\n\nA **prismatic affinity** is a type of geometric transformation in mathematics, specifically a special kind of **affine transformation** in space. It's also sometimes called an *axial affinity* or *skew affinity*.\n\n## Definition\n\nA prismatic affinity is a transformation of three-dimensional space that:\n\n1. **Fixes a plane** (called the *plane of affinity* or *base plane*) point by point\n2. **Maps every other point** along lines parallel to a fixed direction (called the *direction of affinity*)\n3. The ratio of distances from the base plane is constant for all points\n\n## Key Properties\n\n- **Parallel lines remain parallel** after the transformation\n- **The base plane remains invariant** (every point on it stays put)\n- **Lines parallel to the direction of affinity** map to themselves\n- **Volumes are scaled** by the affinity ratio\n- It can be either **orthogonal** (when the direction is perpendicular to the base plane) or **oblique/skew**\n\n## Mathematical Form\n\nIf the base plane is $z = 0$ and the direction is the $z$-axis, an orthogonal prismatic affinity with ratio $k$ takes the form:\n\n$$\n(x, y, z) \\mapsto (x, y, kz)\n$$\n\nFor an oblique version with direction vector $\\vec{d} = (a, b, 1)$:\n\n$$\n(x, y, z) \\mapsto (x + (k-1)az,\\ y + (k-1)bz,\\ kz)\n$$\n\n## Applications\n\nPrismatic affinities are used in:\n- **Descriptive geometry** for constructing projections\n- **Computer graphics** for shearing and scaling operations\n- **Crystallography** for describing certain symmetry operations\n- **Engineering drawing** for creating axonometric views\n\nThe 2D analogue is called a **homologous affinity** or simply an *axial affinity*, where a line (rather than a plane) is fixed pointwise.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any particular aspect, such as the matrix representation or specific applications?",
